  "response": "Exchanging Indian \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes, especially on a commission basis, requires caution. Since the demonetization of these notes in 2016, old \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes are no longer legal tender. However, there are some important points to consider:\n\n1. **Old Notes (Pre-2016):**  \n   If you have the old \u20b9500 or \u20b91000 notes, they are invalid for transactions or exchange. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) provided a specific window for exchanging these notes, which has now closed.\n\n2. **New Notes (Post-2016):**  \n   The new \u20b9500 and \u20b92000 notes introduced after demonetization are valid and can be used without issue.\n\n3. **Beware of Scams:**  \n   Be cautious of individuals or agents offering to exchange old notes for a commission. These are often scams, and you may end up losing money or facing legal consequences.\n\n4. **Legal Implications:**  \n   Attempting to exchange old notes outside authorized channels can lead to legal trouble, as it may be considered an attempt to launder money or engage in illegal activities.\n\n5. **Official RBI Guidelines:**  \n   If you still hold old \u20b9500 or \u20b91000 notes, you can check the official RBI website for any updates or special provisions, though it\u2019s unlikely they\u2019ll be exchanged at this point.\n\nIf you\u2019re looking to exchange valid currency, it\u2019s best to do so through authorized banks or currency exchange services. Always ensure that your transactions are legal and transparent to avoid any issues.",
